13:59.613 --> 14:01.913
I'm scared for him.
The police look at him,

14:01.949 --> 14:04.416
and they don't see
a 10-year-old little boy.

14:04.452 --> 14:06.785
They don't know
that he on the honor roll.

14:08.021 --> 14:09.755
He a terror to them.

14:11.124 --> 14:12.758
<i>Fear, though,
is not only felt</i>

14:12.793 --> 14:14.860
<i>by the community
but by police as well.</i>

14:14.895 --> 14:17.829
<i>The recent calculated
attacks on officers</i>

14:17.864 --> 14:20.398
<i>have sent shock waves
through precincts nationwide.</i>

14:26.373 --> 14:27.872
<i>Police across
the country</i>

14:27.907 --> 14:29.073
on high alert right now,

14:29.108 --> 14:32.743
after four police officers were
shot in four separate cities.

14:32.778 --> 14:36.513
We've lost 12 officers. I don't
care what race they are.

14:36.548 --> 14:38.948
They were shot
and killed in 30 days.

14:38.984 --> 14:42.519
This officer was driving down
the road and was ambushed.

14:42.554 --> 14:44.020
<i>Shots fired! Officer down!</i>

14:44.055 --> 14:45.756
<i>Shots fired! Officer down!</i>

14:49.127 --> 14:51.560
<i>The St. Louis
Police Wives' Association</i>

14:51.596 --> 14:54.764
<i>shared their fears
about the escalating violence.</i>

14:54.799 --> 14:56.064
We call it a crisis,

14:56.100 --> 14:58.534
because law enforcement
has become

14:58.569 --> 15:01.837
disenfranchised with the
community, or disconnected,

15:01.873 --> 15:07.074
seeing protest just because
they're wearing a uniform.

15:11.615 --> 15:14.382
<i>Are you concerned
that it's gotten more unsafe?</i>

15:14.418 --> 15:17.251
<i> We know it. Just
sitting at this table here,</i>

15:17.287 --> 15:21.856
you have two women whose husbands
have almost been killed--

15:21.892 --> 15:23.124
myself and her husband.

15:23.159 --> 15:25.358
- And your husbands have been shot at?
Uh-huh.

15:25.394 --> 15:26.993
- Shot.
- Oh, shot? And they've--

15:27.029 --> 15:29.430
- They've all been shot at.
- They've all been shot at.

15:29.465 --> 15:30.864
All of your husbands
have been shot at.

15:30.900 --> 15:33.901
Mine-- mine particularly,
was ambushed.

15:33.936 --> 15:38.872
We had protesters show up in front
of the hospital, protesting...

15:38.908 --> 15:40.540
Yes, they did.

15:40.575 --> 15:43.609
...with signs that said,
"Well, how does it feel?"

15:43.644 --> 15:44.944
Yes, they did.

15:44.979 --> 15:47.613
We're also sitting at home, now,

15:47.649 --> 15:50.950
watching our communities implode.
Mm-hmm.

15:50.985 --> 15:54.754
But now, we can
at least all admit

15:54.789 --> 15:56.355
that we have a problem.

15:56.390 --> 15:58.623
That's-- that's
the first thing, okay?

15:58.659 --> 16:02.427
So, revolution, problem,
now let's seek some solutions.

16:02.463 --> 16:06.097
I, Donald John Trump,
do solemnly swear...

16:06.132 --> 16:08.099
<i>As the new administration
prepares to pull back</i>

16:08.134 --> 16:10.034
<i>federal oversight on police,</i>

16:10.070 --> 16:11.770
<i>one thing is clear...</i>

16:11.805 --> 16:14.672
<i>...policing needs to change
if lives are to be saved.</i>

16:14.707 --> 16:19.543
<i>And ultimately, reform is in the
hands of local police departments.</i>

16:19.579 --> 16:20.845
I don't know how to fix poverty.

16:20.880 --> 16:23.948
I don't know how to deal with
education systems that are failing.

16:23.983 --> 16:26.016
What I do know
is how to do police work,

16:26.051 --> 16:27.685
and when those things
don't happen,

16:27.720 --> 16:31.355
we're left with communities that have
greater demands on their law enforcement.

16:31.390 --> 16:32.789
Well, we have to solve them,

16:32.824 --> 16:35.492
or we're going to continue to do
this over and over and over again.

16:36.895 --> 16:39.328
<i>People don't understand
what we deal with.</i>

16:39.364 --> 16:42.198
You know, until you're
actually put in those shoes

16:42.233 --> 16:45.602
and you have to try to defend
yourself or someone else.

16:45.637 --> 16:49.337
We're to the point where
you have so much division.

16:49.373 --> 16:50.973
Both sides need
to get it together.

16:51.008 --> 16:53.509
<i>You'll notice
around the country</i>

16:53.544 --> 16:57.445
<i>more and more officers
are beginning to speak out.</i>

16:57.481 --> 17:00.616
We have to be the change
that needs to be.

17:04.755 --> 17:07.221
More than 36 million
American adults

17:07.256 --> 17:08.623
live with physical disabilities,

17:08.657 --> 17:11.258
<i>but rapid advancements
in bio-engineering</i>

17:11.292 --> 17:13.394
<i>and robotics have
brought about a revolution</i>

17:13.429 --> 17:17.263
<i>in bionic technology that
is realizing possibilities</i>

17:17.299 --> 17:21.101
that, up until now, would have
been considered science fiction.

17:21.137 --> 17:24.037
Wilbert Cooper has been
following this story.

17:41.989 --> 17:43.589
I'm here in Zurich, Switzerland,

17:43.624 --> 17:44.423
for the Cybathlon,

17:44.458 --> 17:46.391
which is the first-ever
bionic Olympics,

17:46.427 --> 17:49.227
to see the state-of-the-art
in assistive technology.

18:08.949 --> 18:12.383
<i>The Cybathlon is the
first competition of its kind,</i>

18:12.418 --> 18:14.585
<i>featuring teams
from around the world,</i>

18:14.620 --> 18:17.120
<i>showcasing the most
advanced technologies</i>

18:17.155 --> 18:19.022
<i>for people with disabilities.</i>

18:19.058 --> 18:20.323
Can you tell me about your hand?

18:20.358 --> 18:22.392
It has five motors,

18:22.427 --> 18:23.961
and I control those motors

18:23.996 --> 18:26.063
by electro-impulses
from my muscle.

18:26.098 --> 18:30.266
And the wicked one is... 360.

18:30.302 --> 18:31.366
That's cool.

18:31.402 --> 18:33.569
Where is it gonna go from here?
I don't know.

18:33.605 --> 18:36.438
How good's your imagination?

18:36.474 --> 18:38.908
<i>With the exoskeleton
that we brought today,</i>

18:38.943 --> 18:41.176
I can actually take
a normal walk now,

18:41.212 --> 18:43.145
and, you know,
step-by-step,

18:43.180 --> 18:44.379
there is no hesitation.

18:44.415 --> 18:45.848
It's one, two, three, four.

18:56.059 --> 18:58.760
<i>It just gives me the
ability to do the simple things</i>

18:58.795 --> 19:00.595
<i>in life that you don't
really think about.</i>

19:02.599 --> 19:04.798
For me, it--
it means freedom.

19:08.303 --> 19:10.804
<i>New developments
in scientific research</i>

19:10.840 --> 19:13.340
<i>and practical engineering
are pushing boundaries,</i>

19:13.375 --> 19:15.042
<i>making that freedom possible.</i>

19:15.077 --> 19:18.045
It's phenomenal to be in
this place and see the way

19:18.080 --> 19:20.948
that technology is transforming
and changing people's lives.

19:25.319 --> 19:27.286
<i>And some of the
most advanced developments</i>

19:27.321 --> 19:30.456
<i>are actually happening
inside the human body.</i>

19:31.726 --> 19:32.825
<i>A team from Cleveland, Ohio,</i>

19:32.861 --> 19:35.862
<i>is using an implanted device
that restores movement</i>

19:35.897 --> 19:38.097
<i>to those with severe
spinal cord injuries</i>

19:38.133 --> 19:41.033
<i>by electrically stimulating
their paralyzed muscles.</i>

19:41.068 --> 19:44.402
I have implants
in both sides of my belly

19:44.437 --> 19:48.173
to which these wires
are attached.

19:48.208 --> 19:51.442
Little box here tells
where my legs are

19:51.478 --> 19:53.845
and when to fire which muscles.

19:53.881 --> 19:58.549
So, below my arms,
without the system,

19:58.584 --> 20:01.518
the only thing I can do
is wiggle my big toe.

20:04.123 --> 20:05.890
How did you become paralyzed?

20:05.925 --> 20:08.525
It was a skiing accident
on a family trip

20:08.561 --> 20:10.527
in Lake Tahoe, California.

20:10.563 --> 20:14.964
<i>And we were on, of course,
the last run of the day,</i>

20:15.000 --> 20:19.135
I had an accident where my skis
were caught under a branch,

20:19.171 --> 20:21.470
and I flew out of the skis

20:21.506 --> 20:25.075
and hit a big granite
boulder head-first

20:25.110 --> 20:28.078
and fractured a bone in my neck.

20:28.113 --> 20:30.112
It left me paralyzed
immediately.

20:31.215 --> 20:33.448
And with the system,

20:33.483 --> 20:37.953
obviously, this is over the top.

20:37.988 --> 20:40.222
<i>Now, for the first
time since his accident,</i>

20:40.257 --> 20:42.057
<i>Mark is competing athletically.</i>

20:51.300 --> 20:54.368
<i>Pioneering this technology
is Dr. Ronald Triolo,</i>

20:54.403 --> 20:56.904
<i>a professor at Case Western
Reserve University</i>

20:56.940 --> 20:58.039
<i>and the executive director</i>

20:58.074 --> 21:00.775
<i>of the VA's Advanced
Platform Technology Center.</i>

21:00.810 --> 21:04.477
<i>We're at the verge of
an era where robotic technology</i>

21:04.512 --> 21:08.448
can make a real impact
in people's lives.

21:16.691 --> 21:19.659
<i>Our long-term goal
is to make the technology</i>

21:19.694 --> 21:21.026
as invisible as possible.

21:21.062 --> 21:25.798
<i>That means that we have some
sort of man-machine interface</i>

21:25.833 --> 21:29.235
that is completely internal
and indistinguishable.

21:29.270 --> 21:31.871
It's just stretching
what it means to be human.

21:48.889 --> 21:51.455
This technology
has helped you win this race,

21:51.491 --> 21:52.757
and do something
really incredible.

21:52.793 --> 21:55.159
What can you say
about the way technology

21:55.194 --> 21:57.761
is sort of integrating itself
into our lives right now?

21:57.797 --> 21:59.496
What do you think
that holds for the future?

21:59.531 --> 22:01.265
Getting deep
into the human body,

22:01.300 --> 22:03.834
getting technology
into the human body is

22:03.869 --> 22:05.936
one of the last frontiers,

22:05.971 --> 22:09.439
and I think that
we've tapped into it.

22:09.474 --> 22:12.775
There's some great things--
not just what you've seen today,

22:12.811 --> 22:15.812
but there's some great things
being done medically

22:15.847 --> 22:17.947
through technology as well.

22:17.982 --> 22:21.317
<i>And the technologies
on display in Zurich</i>

22:21.352 --> 22:22.484
<i>are only the beginning.</i>

22:22.520 --> 22:25.254
<i>Researchers around the world
have begun experimenting</i>

22:25.290 --> 22:29.657
<i>with implanting electronic devices
directly into the human brain.</i>

22:29.693 --> 22:32.027
<i>In Columbus, Ohio,
we met with one</i>

22:32.062 --> 22:34.129
<i>of the world's foremost
neurosurgeons,</i>

22:34.164 --> 22:36.531
<i>Dr. Ali Rezai.</i>

22:36.566 --> 22:38.800
Now, in the past
decade especially,

22:38.836 --> 22:41.336
we've learned so much
about the human brain,

22:41.371 --> 22:44.039
the human nervous system,
that's now allowing us

22:44.074 --> 22:48.042
to use technology to help patients
with nervous system disorders.

22:48.077 --> 22:52.512
So, it's a very active area
of technology that evolving.

22:53.916 --> 22:56.450
<i>Today, Dr. Rezai
is performing a procedure</i>

22:56.485 --> 22:57.852
<i>called deep brain stimulation</i>

22:57.887 --> 23:00.921
<i>on a patient suffering
from Parkinson's disease.</i>

23:13.501 --> 23:15.668
<i>Deep brain
stimulation, or DBS,</i>

23:15.703 --> 23:18.371
<i>involves a tiny stimulator
that we implant</i>

23:18.406 --> 23:21.240
<i>in a part of the brain
to shut down the tremor</i>

23:21.275 --> 23:23.775
<i>and to reduce
the excessive movements</i>

23:23.810 --> 23:25.777
<i>that are caused by Parkinson's.</i>

24:08.720 --> 24:10.720
<i>As the electrode
enters the brain,</i>

24:10.755 --> 24:13.855
<i>Dr. Rezai is able to listen
to the neural activity</i>

24:13.891 --> 24:16.792
<i>in order to locate the area
causing the tremors.</i>

24:55.730 --> 24:58.398
- The left arm.
- Good.

25:11.446 --> 25:13.846
Yeah.

25:18.552 --> 25:20.718
<i>The operation is
nearly instantaneous.</i>

25:20.753 --> 25:25.056
<i>80% improvement displays the
power of deep brain stimulation.</i>

25:25.092 --> 25:28.759
<i>The procedure can be used for conditions
from epilepsy to chronic pain,</i>

25:28.795 --> 25:31.696
<i>and scientists are exploring its
use to treat severe depression.</i>

25:31.731 --> 25:36.700
<i>In Dublin, Ohio, we saw an even
more advanced brain implant system.</i>

25:44.443 --> 25:46.610
<i>Ian Burkhart, a quadriplegic,</i>

25:46.645 --> 25:49.446
<i>is another patient
of Dr. Rezai's.</i>

25:49.482 --> 25:51.448
<i>After suffering a traumatic
injury, he was implanted</i>

25:51.484 --> 25:55.684
<i>with one of the most
cutting-edge neurotechnologies.</i>

25:57.122 --> 25:58.821
<i>Just a few
days after finishing</i>

25:58.856 --> 26:00.156
my freshman year at college,

26:00.191 --> 26:02.892
I went on vacation
with some friends

26:02.927 --> 26:05.461
and dove into a wave
in the ocean,

26:05.497 --> 26:09.132
and I didn't know where I was diving
was actually only a few feet deep.

26:10.467 --> 26:13.635
So, I initially hit
my head extremely hard

26:13.670 --> 26:15.670
and that caused me
to break my neck.

26:15.705 --> 26:19.774
I lost all function
from about my elbows down

26:19.809 --> 26:22.744
and all feeling from the
middle of my chest down.

26:22.779 --> 26:27.415
I can't move any of my individual
fingers or open and close my hand.

26:27.450 --> 26:30.384
So, after I had my accident,
I was always looking towards

26:30.420 --> 26:33.487
<i>what type of technology could
help me in my everyday life.</i>

26:33.523 --> 26:36.290
And one thing led to another,
and I decided to get...

26:36.325 --> 26:40.661
brain surgery and be the
first person to move my hand

26:40.696 --> 26:42.263
with my own brain.

26:44.132 --> 26:45.598
<i>Ian is the only human being</i>

26:45.633 --> 26:48.301
who's had this technology
applied that allows him

26:48.336 --> 26:51.071
to move his hands
using his thoughts.

26:55.243 --> 26:58.945
<i>A small port on Ian's
head opens a direct channel</i>

26:58.980 --> 27:01.480
<i>between his brain
and a computer.</i>

27:03.150 --> 27:06.385
<i>The computer interprets
Ian's brain signals,</i>

27:06.420 --> 27:09.388
<i>his thoughts, and then
links those thoughts</i>

27:09.423 --> 27:11.423
<i>to a external wearable garment,</i>

27:11.459 --> 27:14.926
<i>so, basically, the sleeve that Ian
wears that allows him to move,</i>

27:14.962 --> 27:18.829
and this is called
brain-computer interface.

27:18.864 --> 27:20.465
<i>When Ian thinks about moving,</i>

27:20.500 --> 27:22.500
<i>the computer delivers
electrical impulses</i>

27:22.535 --> 27:25.936
<i>to his high-tech sleeve,
allowing him to use his hands</i>

27:25.972 --> 27:28.806
<i>in ways that haven't been
possible since his accident.</i>

27:28.841 --> 27:31.576
All right, I'm starting
in three, two, one.

27:48.727 --> 27:51.161
<i>After four years
of not moving a flicker,</i>

27:51.196 --> 27:53.329
<i>he started moving
a little bit two years ago,</i>

27:53.364 --> 27:56.365
<i>and now he's able to perform
more sophisticated movements.</i>

27:56.400 --> 27:58.834
<i>and right now he's able
to do those movements</i>

27:58.869 --> 28:00.836
<i>much faster than he did before.</i>

28:05.176 --> 28:06.875
That's amazing.
That was awesome.

28:06.910 --> 28:08.844
That went really well.
That was your best time.

28:08.879 --> 28:12.079
That went really well.
That was good.

28:12.115 --> 28:15.283
<i> Restoring functionality
through brain-computer interfaces</i>

28:15.318 --> 28:17.352
<i>has the potential
to dramatically improve</i>

28:17.387 --> 28:19.254
<i>the lives of those
with disabilities</i>

28:19.289 --> 28:24.025
<i>and could even open up entirely
new avenues of human experience.</i>

28:24.060 --> 28:28.094
Right now, there's a convergence
of so many elements

28:28.130 --> 28:29.963
in terms
of technological innovation.

28:29.998 --> 28:33.933
<i>This is really opening up a whole
new window into possibilities,</i>

28:33.969 --> 28:36.936
<i>so you're able
to record brain activity</i>

28:36.972 --> 28:38.838
<i>and link it within milliseconds</i>

28:38.874 --> 28:40.974
to result
in purposeful movements,

28:41.009 --> 28:44.310
<i>that can be potentially a means
by which we can be able</i>

28:44.345 --> 28:47.713
<i>to detect other elements
beyond movements.</i>

28:47.748 --> 28:49.549
<i>For example, sensations.</i>

28:49.584 --> 28:51.517
Index.

28:52.820 --> 28:54.019
Pinkie.

28:54.055 --> 28:55.688
<i>Right now is a
fantastic time for us,</i>

28:55.723 --> 28:57.290
<i>because we're learning
so much more,</i>

28:57.325 --> 28:59.659
<i>more than ever before,
about the human brain.</i>

28:59.694 --> 29:01.926
One of the final frontiers.

